ol.li:
First, determine the left-most non-zero column, which will be the first pivot column. In this column, choose a non-zero entry to be the pivot entry. If necessary, use a row exchange to positive the pivot at the top of the column.
\begin{bmatrix} \mid \amp \mid \amp a \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \\ \mid \amp \mid \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \end{bmatrix}
In terms of completing the algorithm, it doesn't matter which non-zero entry we select to be the pivot. For hand-computation, it is typically easier to select a 1 if that is available, as that will make the computations a bit more simple.

Repeat the previous steps with the remaining submatrix below and to the right of the pivot,
\begin{bmatrix} \mid \amp \mid \amp a \amp \ast \amp \ast \amp \ast \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp b \amp \ast \amp \ast \\ \mid \amp \mid \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \ast \amp \ast \end{bmatrix} \qquad \longrightarrow \qquad \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} b \amp \ast \amp \ast \\ 0 \amp \ast \amp \ast \end{bmatrix}}_{\text{submatrix}}
Repeat this process until there are no more non-zero rows to modify.

subsection.example:


    Consider the matrix in REF,


    \begin{bmatrix}
    1 \amp 0 \amp -5 \amp 1 \\
    0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\
    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
    \end{bmatrix}

which is the augmented matrix of the linear system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
    x \amp \amp -5z \amp = \amp 1 \\
    \amp y \amp + z \amp = \amp 4 \\
    \amp \amp 0 \amp = \amp 0
    \end{array}

At this point, notice that the third equation is the true statement (or tautology) 0 = 0. Intuitively, this means that while there were originally 3 equations that constrained the possible solutions, one of those equations were superfluous. Then, any solution (x,y,z) only has to satisfy the remaining two equations. In short, there are 3 variables, but only 2 constraints. In this case, for example, if we choose an arbitrary value of z, say z = t, then we can solve for x and y in equation 1 and 2, respectively, and get a solution of the system. In particular,

    \begin{cases}
    x = 1 + 5t \\
    y = 4 - t \\
    z = t
    \end{cases}

Then, any tuple of the form (1+5t,4-t,t) (where t \in \mathbb{R} is any number) will be a solution to the system. In particular, there are infinitely many solutions of the system. Here, z is called a free variable, because it can take on any value to generate a solution of the system.

Consider the matrix in REF,

    \begin{bmatrix}
    1 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\
    0 \amp -1 \amp -4 \amp 7 \\
    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2
    \end{bmatrix}

which corresponds to the linear system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
        x \amp -3y \amp + z \amp = \amp 1 \\
        \amp -y \amp -4 z \amp = \amp 4 \\
        \amp \amp 0 \amp = \amp 2
    \end{array}

The 3rd equation is the false statement (or, contradiction) 0 = 2, so the system has no solution. This is because, no matter what the values of x, y, z, it is not possible for the third equation to be satisfied. A solution of the system must make every equation true, so no such solution exists. Thus, the system is inconsistent.
